 Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saint-Clair","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French Canadian and American French   St. Clair   1 or French <b>Saint-Clair</b> (see   St. Clair   2). This form of the surname is no longer found in France."],"variants":[{"name":"St. Clair","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Sinclair  . This is also a French Canadian and American French altered form of the same surname.","French (<b>Saint-Clair</b>): habitational name from any of several places, e.g. in Normandy, named Saint-Clair (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Clarus). Compare   Saintclair  .","Haitian (also <b>Saint-Clair</b>): ornamental name or nickname, perhaps ironic, composed of French <i>saint</i> ‘saint’ or ‘holy’ and <i>clair</i> ‘clear’ or ‘lightness’. Alternatively, perhaps of the same French origin as 2 above. Compare   Saintclair  ."]}]},{"name":"Basilie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Pedro, Domingo, Roberto, Carlos, Ricardo, Albertino, Alejandro, Almario, Altagracia, Andres, Armando.  Portuguese Ilidio.  Italian Antonio, Gennaro, Anastasio, Federico, Marco, Quirino.","Italian; Portuguese (<b>Basílio</b>): from the personal name <i>Basilio</i>, <i>Basílio</i>, from Latin <i>Basilius</i> (see   Basil  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Basil","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Basileios</i> ‘royal’ (a derivative of <i>basileus</i> ‘king’). This name was borne by  St Basil  the Great (  <i>c.</i>330–379 ), bishop of Caesarea, a theologian regarded as one of the Fathers of the Eastern Church. It was also the name of several early saints martyred in the East."]},{"name":"Bacilio","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico and Peru): variant spelling of   Basilio  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Basilie de Saint-Clair was born about 1085, in France. She married Eudes de Dammartin of Norton and Mendlesham about 1098. They were the parents of at least 5 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1085–":"umbes 1085–Surnud","1082–1130":"1082–1130","1106–1183":"1106–1183","1110–1183":"1110–1183","1113–Male":"1113–Surnud","1115–1179":"1115–1179","1120–1157":"1120–1157","1085–Female":"1085–Surnud","ca 1098":"umbes 1098","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","abt 1120":"umbes 1120","1085":"1085","1183":"1183","1082":"1082","1106":"1106","Abt 1085":"umbes 1085","1115":"1115","Abt 1113":"umbes 1113","1157":"1157","1179":"1179","1113":"1113","about 1115":"umbes 1115","Dammartin, Seine-et-Marne, Ile-de-France, France":"Dammartin-sur-Tigeaux, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Mendlesham, Hertismere, Suffolk, England":"Mendlesham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , France":"Prantsusmaa","Mendlesham, Hartismere, Suffolk, England":"Mendlesham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1085–":"noin 1085–Kuollut","1082–1130":"1082–1130","1106–1183":"1106–1183","1110–1183":"1110–1183","1113–Male":"1113–Kuollut","1115–1179":"1115–1179","1120–1157":"1120–1157","1085–Female":"1085–Kuollut","ca 1098":"noin 1098","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","abt 1120":"noin 1120","1085":"1085","1183":"1183","1082":"1082","1106":"1106","Abt 1085":"noin 1085","1115":"1115","Abt 1113":"noin 1113","1157":"1157","1179":"1179","1113":"1113","